#: ../../../reference/random/generated/numpy.random.Generator.laplace.rst:4
msgid "numpy.random.Generator.laplace"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/random/generated/numpy.random.Generator.laplace.rst:8
msgid "method"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:2
msgid ""
"Draw samples from the Laplace or double exponential distribution with "
"specified location (or mean) and scale (decay)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:5
msgid ""
"The Laplace distribution is similar to the Gaussian/normal distribution, but "
"is sharper at the peak and has fatter tails. It represents the difference "
"between two independent, identically distributed exponential random "
"variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:0
msgid "Parameters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:13
msgid "**loc**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:-1
msgid "float or array_like of floats, optional"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:13
msgid "The position, :math:`\\mu`, of the distribution peak. Default is 0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:17
msgid "**scale**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:16
msgid ""
":math:`\\lambda`, the exponential decay. Default is 1. Must be non- negative."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:25
msgid "**size**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:-1
msgid "int or tuple of ints, optional"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:20
msgid ""
"Output shape.  If the given shape is, e.g., ``(m, n, k)``, then ``m * n * "
"k`` samples are drawn.  If size is ``None`` (default), a single value is "
"returned if ``loc`` and ``scale`` are both scalars. Otherwise, ``np."
"broadcast(loc, scale).size`` samples are drawn."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:0
msgid "Returns"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:37
msgid "**out**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:-1
msgid "ndarray or scalar"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:30
msgid "Drawn samples from the parameterized Laplace distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:40
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:41
msgid "It has the probability density function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:43
msgid ""
"f(x; \\mu, \\lambda) = \\frac{1}{2\\lambda}\n"
"\\exp\\left(-\\frac{|x - \\mu|}{\\lambda}\\right).\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._generator.Generator.laplace:46
msgid ""
"The first law of Laplace, from 1774, states that the frequency of an error "
"can be expressed as an exponential function of the absolute magnitude of the "
"error, which leads to the Laplace distribution. For many problems in "
"economics and health sciences, this distribution seems to model the data "
"better than the standard Gaussian distribution."
msgstr ""

